          <figcaption class="image-caption-wrapper">
            <p data-rte-preserve-empty="true"><em>An example of a box dieline prototype</em></p>
          </figcaption>
        
      
        </figure>
      

    
  


  





  <ol data-rte-list="default"><li><p class=""><strong>Draw your template:</strong> On paper or lightweight cardboard, carefully draw the dimensions of your box. Use a ruler to ensure straight lines and accurate measurements.</p></li><li><p class=""><strong>Cut out a template:</strong> use paper or lightweight cardboard to cut out the dimensions of your box. Be precise with your ruler and scissors.</p></li><li><p class=""><strong>Score and fold:</strong> lightly score along the lines where you’ll fold. This helps the edges stay clean and sharp.</p></li><li><p class=""><strong>Assemble the box:</strong> use tape or glue to assemble the box shape. If your product is heavy, reinforce the mockup with extra tape.</p></li><li><p class=""><strong>Check the fit:</strong> place your product inside to see how it fits. Ensure there’s enough space for protective materials like tissue paper if needed.</p></li></ol><p class="">If creating a mockup feels too advanced, don’t worry—it’s not a required step!</p><h4>STEP 5</h4><h3>Share your measurements for customization</h3><p class="">Once you’ve confirmed your measurements, you’re ready to use them for a custom box template or resize an existing one. If you’re buying a premade template, simply provide your dimensions to the designer (that’s me!) to ensure a perfect fit.</p><h3>Bonus tips for measuring specific products</h3>





















  
  














































  

    

      <figure data-test="image-block-v2-outer-wrapper" class="
            sqs-block-image-figure
